Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
setViaGenMode(25.10)                                      setViaGenMode(25.10)

Name
       setViaGenMode  -  Sets global variables for vias that connect rings and
       stripes when you use  the  addRing,  addStripe,  editPowerVia,  sroute,
       addSplitPowerVia or editAddRoute commands

Syntax
        setViaGenMode

       [-help]

       [-reset]

       [-accuracy_effort {low | medium | high}]

       [-add_pin_to_pin_via {true | false}]

       [-align_merged_stack_via_metals {true | false}]

       [-allow_via_expansion {true | false}]

       [-allow_wire_shape_change {true | false}]

       [-area_only {true | false}]

       [-bot_enclosure {<overhang1 overhang2>}]

       [-create_double_row_cut_via {0 | 1 | 2}]

       [-create_max_row_cut_via {true | false}]

       [-cut_spacing {<x_spacing y_spacing>}]

       [-cutclass_preference  {default  |  {[square]  [bar]  [large]}  |  cut-
       class_name_list} | file_name]

       [-disable_via_merging {true | false}]

       [-extend_out_wire_end {true | false}]

       [-full_cut_via_only {true | false}]

       [-genvia_naming_prefix <viaNamePrefix>]

       [-hookup_contact_max {<distance1_max distance2_max>}]

       [-hookup_contact_pg_track {<start_value pitch_value>}]

       [-hookup_preplace_fix {0 | 1}]

       [-hookup_rail_pair {0 | 1}]

       [-hookup_via_distance  {<distance_value1>  [<distance_value2>  [<bound-
       ary_spacing>]]}]

       [-hookup_via_fixed_grid {true | false}]

       [-hookup_via_min_distance <distance>]

       [-hookup_via_style {none | loose | compact | moderate}]

       [-hookup_via_viarule      {<filler>      {<default>     |{<list_of_via>
       <rule>/<cell_names> }} ...}]

       [-hookup_virtual_trim_grid {default |{-layer -mask1 {-pitch  -core_off-
       set...}}}]

       [-ignore_design_boundary {true | false}]

       [-ignore_DRC {true | false}]

       [-ignore_viarule_enclosure {true | false}]

       [-inherit_wire_status {true | false}]

       [-invoke_verifyGeometry {true | false}]

       [-keep_existing_via {0 | 1 | 2}]

       [-keep_fixed_via {true | false}]

       [-mincut_preference <value>]

       [-optimize_cross_via {true | false}]

       [-optimize_via_on_routing_track {true | false}]

       [-parameterized_via_only {true | false | auto}]

       [-partial_overlap_threshold <float>]

       [-preferred_vias_only {use_lef | open | keep}]

       [-reference_boundary {design|core}]

       [-respect_signal_routes {0 | 1 | 2}]

       [-respect_stdcell_geometry {true | false}]

       [-respect_wire_ndr {true | false}]

       [-set_via_expansion_dir {auto | horizontal | vertical}]

       [-snap_via_center_to_grid {{ layer1 {none | grid | half_grid | either }
       [hard]} layer2 {{none | grid | half_grid | either } [hard]} ... }]

       [-split_long_via_global_grid   {x_offset   x_pitch   x_length_threshold
       x_length_multiplier y_offset y_pitch y_length_threshold y_length_multi-
       plier}]

       [-symmetrical_via_only {true | false | auto}]

       [-top_enclosure {<overhang1 overhang2>}]

       [-use_track_offset {true | false}]

       [-use_trim_metal_enclosure {true | false}]

       [-viarule_preference {default | predefined | generated | <list  of  via
       rule/cell names> | <file_name>}]

       Sets  global variables for vias that connect rings and stripes when you
       use the addRing, addStripe, editPowerVia, sroute,  addSplitPowerVia  or
       editAddRoute commands.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each setViaGenMode parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and  all  its  parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man setViaGenMode

       -accuracy_effort {low | medium | high}
              Controls  the  balance  between  accuracy and runtime during via
              generation.

              * When set to high, viagen checks full DRC rules and creates DRC
                clean vias.

              * When set to medium, viagen runs  DRC  check  in  the  moderate
                mode.

              * When set to low, viagen runs in the quick DRC check mode. With
                this value specified, some available vias may be missed, since
                the conservative rules are checked.

              The  vias  generated  through this parameter are DRC clean. This
              parameter generates vias with reduced  runtime  in  the  special
              scenarios  where  complex DRC rules are triggered. These complex
              rules include (but are not limited to) same metal  aligned  cuts
              spacing.

              Default: high

       -add_pin_to_pin_via {true | false}
              Inserts vias to connect pins between different cover macros.

              Default: false

       -align_merged_stack_via_metals {true | false}
              Aligns merged stack vias.

              Default: false

       -allow_via_expansion {true | false}
              Allows via to expand out of intersection area to meet LEF rules.

              Default: true

       -allow_wire_shape_change {true | false}
              Allows the via to change the metal shape of existing wires.

              Default: true

              Note:  For stack vias, the option is only valid for top and bot-
              tom metal layers.

              Example:

              * -allow_wire_shape_change true

              * -allow_wire_shape_change false

       -area_only {true | false}
              Adds vias only within the specified areas.

              Default: false

       -bot_enclosure {<overhang1 overhang2>}
              Generates vias with the specified bottom enclosure values, with-
              out modifying the LEF file.  Set  the  -ignore_viarule_enclosure
              parameter  to  false while using this parameter, so that the en-
              gine can compare the specified <overhang1> and <overhang2>  val-
              ues with the Via Rule Generate values.

              The  <overhang1>  and  <overhang2>  values must be above the Via
              Rule Generate values.

       -create_double_row_cut_via {0 | 1 | 2}
              Try to expand vias to have one additional cut than original when
              set the option to 1 or 2. That is, expand original vias  of  1xn
              or nx1 cuts to vias of 1x(n+1) or (n+1)x1 cuts.

              * 1: create vias with one additional cut where wires on both top
                and down layers are enough and need no shape change.

              * 2:  create  vias with one additional cut where wires on one of
                the layers are enough.

              Default: 0

               Example:

              * create_double_row_cut 0

              * create_double_row_cut 1

       -create_max_row_cut_via {true | false}
              Try to expand vias to have one additional row or column of  cuts
              than  original  when the option is set to true. It works similar
              to -create_double_row_cut_via except that there is  no  restric-
              tion on one row or one column via.

              Default: false

       -cut_spacing {<x_spacing y_spacing>}
              Generates  vias  with  the specified cut spacing values, without
              modifying the LEF file.

              The <x_spacing> and <y_spacing> values must  be  above  the  Via
              Rule Generate values.

       -cutclass_preference {default | {[square] [bar] [large]} | cut-
       class_name_list | file_name}
              Specifies  the  preference for the via cut class while inserting
              special vias. You can specify one of the following values:

              * default: Prefers to use the first viacell in tech LEF  without
                drc  violation or the first generate viarule to generate maxi-
                mum cut area. For example, cutWidth * cutHeight * cutNumber.

              * square: Prefers to use the SINGLE cut vias. In the LEF defini-
                tion, the cut width and length are usually the  same  and  the
                smallest in that layer. For example, 0.032 by 0.032.

              * bar:  Prefers  to  use the DOUBLE cut vias. In the LEF defini-
                tion, the cut width is the usually the smallest. For  example,
                0.032 by 0.08. It mostly equals to 2 SINGLE cut.

              * large:  Perfers  to use the LARGE cut vias. In the LEF defini-
                tion, the neither the cut width not the length is  the  small-
                est. For example, 0.08 by 0.08, equals to 4 SINGLE cut.

              The  following  figure  shows the difference between the square,
              bar, and large values:

              Note:

              * Parameter setting does not support incremental  specification.
                The last cutClass preference setting is used.

              * When  you  specify {[square] [bar] [large]}, there should be 2
                or 3 cutClass defined in the LEF file. If Innovus detects that
                there are more than 3 or less than 2 cutClasses,  the  setting
                is ignored.

              * In  the specified file, different arguments can be separate by
                space or line break.

       -disable_via_merging {true | false}
              Disables via merging in the layers next to the  followpin  layer
              within the range of two when set the option to true and there is
              followpin  layer  in the design. Triming will be the only way to
              solve drc issues.

              For example, if the followpin layer is in 1, disable via merging
              in 1/2/3; if the followpin layer is in 2, disable via merging in
              1/2/3/4.

              This function helps if the merging  of  via  consums  additional
              wire track unnecessarily.

              Default:

              * false in normal scenarios

              * true for advance nodes (with designs of 12 nm or below)

       -extend_out_wire_end {true | false}
              Allows  via extending outside of existing wire ends at T-type of
              intersection. When set to false, via extending  outside  of  the
              existing wire end are not allowed and may shift inside.

              * -extend_out_wire_end 1

              * -extend_out_wire_end 0

              Default: true

       -full_cut_via_only {true | false}
              Allows the user to create only full cut vias.

              Example

              The  following  via  is generated because of the second left cut
              will have drc violations when the option is set to false.

              * -full_cut_via_only 0

              When set the option to true, only full cut vias will  be  gener-
              ated:

              * -full_cut_via_only 1

                 &

              Default: false

       -genvia_naming_prefix <viaNamePrefix>
              Sets  the  specified prefix name as the prefix for all generated
              vias created by the Innovus software.

              This helps user to select and edit the vias  that  need  further
              modification.

              Default: none

       -hookup_contact_max {<distance1_max distance2_max>}
              Sets the maximum distance to create hookup via from contact, and
              the  maximum  distance between two hookup via on a continuous M0
              PG pin. Following are the parameter values:

              * distance1_max: Specifies the distance required by  every  viaT
                for at least one hookup via drop. For deciding the location of
                hookup  via  for  distance1_max, every viaT needs at least one
                hookup via drop within distance1.

              * distance2_max: Specifies the maximum distance between any  two
                PG hookup vias on a continuous M0 PG pin. An additional hookup
                via must be dropped from the previous hookup via on a continu-
                ous  M0  PG  segment  with  distance2_max. Also, an additional
                hookup via must be dropped within the maximum  distance2  from
                the endpoint of a continuous M0 PG pin.

              Default: 0 0

              The following scenarios depict the usage of this parameter:

              * Deciding the location of hookup via by viaT:

              * Referencing  of the location of viaT by the tool to add hookup
                vias:

              * At least one hookup via needs to be available for each contin-
                uous M0 PG segment, including PG segment at both sides of  the
                row  edge and the PG pin. The continuous M0 PG segment without
                viaT also needs to follow the decision rule of distance2:

              * Four individual via cells are defined  in  the  LEF  file  and
                VIAMAP. Of these, one is 3-cut, two are 2-cut, and the remain-
                ing  one  is  1-cut. The further breakup of these via cells is
                mentioned below:

                * 3-cut via cells: Include three v0 cuts, three m0 metals, and
                  one m1 metals

                * 2-cut via cells: Include two v0 cuts, two m0 metals, and one
                  m1 metals

                * 1-cut via cell: Include one v0 cuts, one m0 metals, and  one
                  m1 metals

       -hookup_contact_pg_track {<start_value pitch_value>}
              Sets  start  point and the pitch of PG track used by hookup con-
              tact. Following are the parameter values:

              * start_value: Specifies the location of the first PG track.

              * pitch_value: Specifies the distance (steps) between two  adja-
                cent  PG  tracks. It needs to be an integer multiple of the m1
                pitch.

              Note: The PG track needs to be aligned with the m1 track.

              Default: 0 0

       -hookup_preplace_fix {0 | 1}
              Enhances the hookup via generation runtime during the DRC check.

              This parameter works only in the multiple-CPU processing mode.

              Default: 0

       -hookup_rail_pair {0 | 1}
              Adds hookup via over the pairing M0 followpins that are distrib-
              uted on both sides of a row with specially defined  viacells  at
              LEF file. Note that while using this parameter, the PG pins need
              to  be  on  track, and the width of the M0 followpin needs to be
              uniform.

              This parameter works only with setting the loose  value  of  the
              -hookup_via_style  parameter.  Three viacells are defined in the
              LEF file. One of those is  2-cut,  and  the  remaining  two  are
              1-cut. Refer to their details below:

              * 2-cut viacell = Two v0 cuts + Two m0 metals + One m1 metals

              * 1-cut viacell = One v0 cuts + One m0 metals + One m1 metals

              For  the  1-cut viacell, m1 needs to overlap completely with M2.
              If this is not possible, the viacell will not be generated.  Re-
              fer to the example below:

              Default: 0

       -hookup_via_distance {<distance_value1> [<distance_value2> [<bound-
       ary_spacing>]]}
              Enables  control to put the first pg via for each followpin. You
              can use this parameter in  the  following  ways:-hookup_via_dis-
              tance {distance_value1}

              -hookup_via_distance {distance_value1 distance_value2}

              -hookup_via_distance   {distance_value1  distance_value2  bound-
              ary_spacing}

              Following are the parameter's various possible values:

              *

                * distance_value1: Specifies the distance (step)  between  via
                  stacks  and  is rounded down to M1 pitch*n. Default value is
                  M1 pitch*4.

                * <distance_value2>: Specifies the distance between via stacks
                  on filler cell. This value can work with all hookup  styles.
                  Default  value  is M1 pitch*4. It indicates the via distance
                  when two neighboring via stacks are over filler cells. Refer
                  to the figure below:

                * <boundary_spacing>: Specifies the distance between the first
                  via and core boundary. It also refers the  minimum  distance
                  between the last via and core boundary.

       -hookup_via_fixed_grid {true | false}
              When  set  to false (default value), the added hookup via can be
              shifted to avoid DRC. When set as true, the hookup via can  only
              be added at the fixed grid.

              The  fixed  grid works with -hookup_via_style. For the loose and
              moderate styles, the hookup via will be removed, if it has  DRC,
              when  created.  For  the  compact  style, the hookup via will be
              kept, whether or not it has DRC.

              The fixed grid is controlled by the following parameter:

              -hookup_via_distance {distance_value1  [distance_value2  [bound-
              ary_spacing]]}

              Here:

              *

                * distance_value1 is the pitch of grid.

                * boundary_spacing  is the distance between the first grid and
                  core boundary.

                * The fixed grid does not get influenced by the shape  of  the
                  design or macros.

                * distance_value2 needs to be set same as distance_value1.

              Below is an example of formation fixed grid using boundary_spac-
              ing  and  distance_value1.  Note  that all the vias of different
              lines need to be aligned.

              Below is an example of DRC control for the  loose  and  moderate
              types  of  hookup via styles. Here, the hookup vias are removed,
              if DRC exists.

              Below is an example of DRC  control  for  the  compact  type  of
              hookup  via  style. Here, the hookup via will be kept, irrespec-
              tive of the existence of DRC.

              Default: false

       -hookup_via_min_distance <distance>
              Specifies the minimum constrained distance between two PG  vias.
              This parameter works with the distance between:

              * Two newly added PG vias

              * Existing PG vias and newly added PG vias on the followpin

              Default: min

       -hookup_via_style {none | loose | compact | moderate}
              Sets hookup via style. The hookup via works between two parallel
              metal  layers (like M0 and M2, or M1 and M3). Assuming it for M0
              and M2, viagen adds stack vias between M0 and  M2  according  to
              the hookup via settings.

              The  associated functionality of various options is provided be-
              low:

              * none: No via hookup style is set. This is the default value.

              * loose: The tool inserts vias between paralleled wires with the
                specified step in  -hookup_via_distance.  The  center  of  the
                left-most  via  needs  to be on the track, which is inside the
                intersection. The via also needs to be  inside  the  intersec-
                tion. If a via stack (like stack3) cannot be dropped at a cer-
                tain step position (dot line area in the figure below) because
                of the DRC violation, it is moved to a closer or farther posi-
                tion with the previous stack (stack2) to ensure DRC clean. Ad-
                ditionally, the next via (stack4) needs to keep the step value
                with  the  original  position of moved stack (dot line area in
                the figure below).

                If DRC clean does not occurs, the via stack is removed,  refer
                to the figure below:

                Note: The hookup style is loose by default, if the via map ta-
                ble does not exist.

              * compact:  If  a via stack (like stack3) cannot be dropped at a
                certain step position (dot line area in the figure below)  be-
                cause  of DRC violation, it is moved to a closer position with
                the previous stack (stack2) to ensure DRC clean. And the  next
                via  (stack4)  needs  to keep the step value with the said via
                (stack3). Refer to the figure below:

                If DRC clean does not occurs by moving the stack,  insert  the
                via  stack at the original position with DRC violation marker.
                Refer to the figure below:

                Note: The hookup style is compact by default, if the  via  map
                table exists.

              * moderate:  If a via stack (like stack3) cannot be dropped at a
                certain step position (dotted line area in the  figure  below)
                due  to  the DRC violation, it is moved to a closer or farther
                position with the previous stack (stack2) to ensure DRC clean.
                If the via stack (stack3) is dropped to a closer position with
                the previous stack (stack2), the next via  (stack4)  needs  to
                keep  the  step value with the said stack (stack3). If the via
                stack (stack6) is dropped to a farther position with the  pre-
                vious  stack (stack5), the next via (stack7) needs to keep the
                step value with the original position of the moved stack.

                If DRC clean is not occurred, viaGen checks  the  next  tracks
                followed  to  insert  the  via  stack at the nearest DRC clean
                track.

       -hookup_via_viarule {<filler> {<default> |{<list_of_via>
       <rule>/<cell_names> }} ...}
              Specifies the preferred viarule for  the  designated  cell  area
              during the hookup via generation. The <default> value of the pa-
              rameter follows the rule of the -viarule_preference parameter to
              generate  a  hookup via. The <list_of_via rule/cell_names> value
              uses the list of via rules or cells as the preferred  usage  for
              filler    cell   during   the   hookup   via   generation.   The
              -hookup_via_viarule parameter  can  also  work  with  the  -pre-
              ferred_vias_only parameter to use different types of viarule or-
              ders for filler cell to be DRC clean.

       -hookup_virtual_trim_grid {default |{-layer -mask1 {-pitch -core_off-
       set...}}}
              Creates  a  virtual  trim grid for PG hookup via generation. The
              created virtual trim grid should align with the via metal of the
              newly created hookup via. When this parameter is specified,  the
              existing trim grid is ignored.

              To honor the existing trim grid, either remove this parameter or
              define  the  existing  trim  grid  within  this  parameter.  The
              -core_offset parameter is calculated from the bottom core bound-
              ary to the center of the first grid.

              Note: The width value for this parameter is taken from  the  LEF
              file.

              Default: ""

       -ignore_design_boundary {true | false}
              Specifies whether a via can be extended out of the design bound-
              ary (floorplan area).

              * When set to true, viagen generates vias and ignores the design
                boundary.

              * When set to false, viagen tries to shift vias first inside the
                boundary  area.  If  it does not overlap with the intersection
                point after shifting, viagen deletes it. If it  overlaps  with
                the  intersection  point after shifting with DRC clean, viagen
                keeps it.

              See the figure below for understanding the usage of this parame-
              ter:

              Default: false

       -ignore_DRC {true | false}
              Setting this option ignores DRC but honors  user-defined  values
              when  creating  vias.  This speeds up via creation during power-
              planning but normally causes DRC violations.

              It should only be used during early  prototyping  to  experiment
              with different power-planning choices that will be updated later
              to be DRC clean.

              Note:  This parameter ignores only the DRC violations from third
              party objects, and the software will still check  the  violation
              inside via.

              Default: false

       -ignore_viarule_enclosure {true | false}
              When  set  to  true, tool will ignore enclosure value in VIARULE
              GENERATE and use the optimized enclosure from cut  layer  rules,
              to  get the maximum number of cuts, minimum via metal shape.When
              set to  false, the enclosure value in VIARULE GENERATE  must  be
              satisfied.  When  this  VIARULE  fails DRC check, tool will take
              next VIARULE or viacell from LEF file.

              Default: true

       -inherit_wire_status {true | false}
              Setting this parameter to true creates via and makes the  status
              of  the  via  inherit  the target wire's status. However, if the
              status of the top or bottom wire is SHIELD,  this  parameter  is
              ignored  and  the  generated vias will always inherit the SHIELD
              status. When this parameter is set to false, via status  is  set
              to ROUTED.

              For  editPowerVia, the target wire is the bottom wire. For other
              commands calling the VIAGEN engine, either the bottom or the top
              wire is the target wire, depends on order of wire read-in. So if
              this parameter is designed to use, editPowerVia  is  the  recom-
              mended command.

              editPowerVia  does  not  delete  or modify vias having status as
              FIXED/COVER.

              Type: Boolean

              Default: false

       -invoke_verifyGeometry {true | false}
              Enables or disables the verify_drc command  called  by  the  via
              generation software.

              * When  set  to true, the via generation software calls the ver-
                ify_drc command to detect any minStep violations,  then  calls
                the  fixVia  -minStep command to fix them. This may impact the
                run-time performance.

              * When set to false, the via generation software will  not  call
                the  verify_drc  command. This may leave minStep violations in
                the design.

              Note:  When   both   the   -invoke_verifyGeometry   and   -opti-
              mize_cross_via  parameters are set to true, and the process node
              is above 10N, DRC violations can be reported.

              Default: false

       -keep_existing_via {0 | 1 | 2}
              If a via exists in an intersection and does not cover the  whole
              intersection,  a  new via is tried to be dropped in the same in-
              tersection. Following are the parameter values:

              * 0: Prevents keeping an existing via, while dropping a new via.

              * 1: Keeps an existing via, while dropping a new via.

              * 2: Keeps an existing via and does not drop a new  via  at  the
                same  intersection,  even when the existing via does not cover
                the whole intersection area.

              Default: 0 (1 for 10 nm designs)

       -keep_fixed_via {true | false}
              Controls whether to preserve the fixed vias or not  when  viaGen
              is called for via generation.

              Default: true

       -mincut_preference <value>
              Specifies the minimum number of cuts during via generation at an
              intersection. For example:

              * If  this  parameter is set to 1, viagen generates at least one
                cut at an intersection, as shown below:

              * If this parameter is set to 2, viagen generates at  least  two
                cuts at an intersection, as shown below:

              Default: 1

       -optimize_cross_via {true | false}
              Generates  vias  with the minimum enclosure value on each layer.
              The different results with false or true values are shown below:

              Default: false

              Note: The default value is true for advanced node (10 NM  and  7
              NM) designs.

       -optimize_via_on_routing_track {true | false}
              Free  up routing tracks by shift or modify the vias minimally in
              intermediate layers and not applied to layers where the wires or
              pins exist. This option only supports  generated  vias  and  not
              predefined vias.

              The default is false.

              Note:  Free up routing tracks against forbidden spacing rule for
              cross  via  and  save routing tracks against end of line spacing
              rule for non cross via. setViaGenMode  -optimize_cross_via  true
              will try to generate cross via.

       -reset Resets  all or specified parameters to their default values. Any
              values that do not already match the default value and  are  re-
              set. will be reported.

       -parameterized_via_only {true | false | auto}
              Generates parameterized vias only. When set to:

              * true,  ViaGen  generates  parameterized vias only, which means
                the DEF syntax of generated vias is with VIARULE. It helps  in
                OpenAcceess designs.

              * false, ViaGen generates both parameterized and fixed vias.

              * auto,  it is true for OpenAccess design, false for non-OpenAc-
                cess design.

              Default:

              * false, when the setOaxMode -saveCdsFixedVias parameter is  en-
                abled in the OpenAccess design.

              * auto, for all other cases.

       -partial_overlap_threshold <float>
              Specifies  ratio  threshold  of  via creation on partial overlap
              wires. The parameter value may range from 0 to 1. The  parameter
              value  1 specifies that no via is dropped on partial overlap in-
              tersection.   The   tool   drops    via    only    when    over-
              lap_width/wire_width  is  greater  than  or equal to the thresh-
              old_value.

              Default: 0

              The following figure depicts parallel overlapping wires:

              The following figures depict vertical cross wires:

       -preferred_vias_only {use_lef | open | keep}
              Generates only the vias set in -viarule_preference.

              Default: use_lef

              Note: This option must be used with the -viarule_preference  op-
              tion.

              When the value of this parameter is set to:

              *

                use_lef:  viarule or via cell specified in -viarule_preference
                is firstly considered. If none of them  fits,  viagen  chooses
                the first DRC clean predefined viarule in the LEF file or auto
                viarule that can bring maximum cut area.

                Note that:

              *

                *

                  * Cut area = single cut area * cut number

                  * Auto   viarule   includes  generate  viarule  and  virtual
                    viarule. Virtual viarule means viarule generated by viagen
                    based on the cut layer rule.

              *

                open:  Only  predefined  viarule  or  via  cell  specified  in
                -viarule_preference  is  considered.  The  first  one with DRC
                clean is kept. If all of them have DRC issues, the whole stack
                is left open.

              *

                keep:  Only  predefined  viarule  or  via  cell  specified  in
                -viarule_preference  is  considered.  The  first  one with DRC
                clean is kept. If all of them have DRC issues, keep the  first
                one  which  is DRC clean with surrounding. If all of them have
                DRC issues with surrounding, the whole stack is left open.

              For more information on predefined viarule and generate viarule,
              see the Via Rule and Generate Via Rule sections respectively  of
              the  LEF  Syntax chapter of the LEF/DEF Language Reference docu-
              ment.

       -reference_boundary {design | core}
              Specifies the offset reference when specifying offset values  in
              the -split_long_via_global_grid parameter. Following are the pa-
              rameter values:

              * design: ViaGen uses design boundary as reference.

              * core: ViaGen uses core boundary as reference.

              Default: -reference_boundary design

       -respect_signal_routes {0 | 1 | 2}
              Controls whether the via generation software honors pre-existing
              signal routes.

              If  set to 1, instructs the via generation software to read pre-
              existing signal routes and avoid creating DRC violations for the
              routes.

              If set to 2, instructs the via generation software to read  pre-
              existing signal routes and avoid creating DRC violations for the
              routes. And improve the runtime of VIA12 process.

              Note: Using this setting can affect software performance signif-
              icantly.

              If set to 0, instructs the via generation software to ignore any
              pre-existing signal routes.

              Note: DRC violations can occur if this setting is used.

              Default: 0

       -respect_stdcell_geometry {true | false}
              Respects geometry inside standard cell patterns.

              Default: false

       -respect_wire_ndr {true | false}
              Controls  spacing between hookup via and signal routes. This al-
              lows viagen to support all NDR rules.

              * When set to false, viagen honors a set of NDR rules, which in-
                clude  PG wire NDR, PG via NDR, pin wire NDR, pin via NDR, and
                signal via NDR.

              * When set to true, the signal wire NDR is also honored, includ-
                ing those listed above with the false value selection of  this
                parameter. This means that setting this parameter to true hon-
                ors all the NDR rules.

              Default: false

       -set_via_expansion_dir {auto | horizontal | vertical}
              Sets via expansion directions.

              Default: auto

       -snap_via_center_to_grid {{ layer1 {none | grid | half_grid | either }
       [hard]} layer2 {{none | grid | half_grid | either } [hard]} ... }
              Specifies the via center alignment style per routing layer. When
              this  parameter  is  set  as  hard, the added via center will be
              snapped to metal track, if the added via will  not  be  extended
              out  of the wire side. If snap via to track will be extended out
              of the wire side, viagen will keep via in the stripe  center  to
              save the routing resource.

              none

              Keeps previous behavior, only snaps to wire center line.

              grid

              Snaps via to the full grid layer track.

              half_grid

              Ignores the full grid. Only snaps to the half_grid layer track.

              either

              Can snap to both full and half grid layer track.

              Default: none

              Examples

              *

                Snap  the  vias  to  each  adjacent up and down layers, except
                Metal1 and Metal2

                *

                  NO stripes on up and down layers

                *

                  Snap the center of via (the whole via, not CUT) to the clos-
                  est track intersection

              *

                Stripes on both up and down layers

                *

                  Generate via on the stripes intersection area (the  same  as
                  previous behavior, NO change)

              *

                Stripe  on  adjacent layer 3 and NO stripe on the other neigh-
                boring routing layer

                *

                  Find the joint point between stripe center and  the  closest
                  track

                *

                  Snap  the  center  of  via  (the whole via, not CUT) to this
                  joint point

              *

                Snap via to the full grid of 4) and half grid of 3

                *

                  setViaGenMode -snap_via_to_grid {3 half_grid 4 grid}

                *

                  Snap via to 3 half grid and 4 full grid

              *

                Snap via to full or half grid of 3 and 4

                *

                  setViaGenMode -snap_via_to_grid {3 either 4 either}

                *

                  Tool could snap to closest full or half grid automatically

              *

                Snap via to track if the via is not extended out of wire side,
                when set as hard

              *

                Keep via in stripe center if the snap via to track is extended
                out of the wire side, when set as hard

       -split_long_via_global_grid {x_offset x_pitch x_length_threshold
       x_length_multiplier y_offset y_pitch y_length_threshold y_length_multi-
       plier}
              Provides options to control global grids so  that  vias  on  the
              grids are in line on x and/or y directions.

              * x_offset,  y_offset:  specifies in microns the offset from de-
                sign boundry

              * x_pitch, y_pitch: specifies in microns the  centre  to  centre
                distance in split vias

              * x_length_threshold,  y_length_threshold: specifies vias longer
                or equal to threshold are being split

              * x_length_multiplier, y_length_multiplier: specifies  unit  via
                length multiplier

              Default: default

       -symmetrical_via_only {true | false | auto}
              By  default the metal-width of a generated-via matches the width
              of the intersection of the metal above and below the via. If the
              width is an odd number of manufacturing grids (mgrids) wide, the
              resulting via cannot  be  represented  by  a  parameterized  via
              (LEF/DEF VIA with VIARULE and parameters or OpenAccess standard-
              Via) because they require a symmetrical enclosure values on both
              sides  of  the cuts. In that case, a fixed-name via (LEF/DEF VIA
              with RECT statements or OpenAccess customVia) must be created to
              have the same width as the intersection area.

              If this option is true, the via metal is enlarged one  mgrid  in
              the odd-mgrid directions order to make the via symmetrical so it
              can  be  represented as a parameterized via. This does not cause
              any DRC violations in general because the via metal should still
              be covered by the metal above/below the via and avoid  any  min-
              step violations.

              Fixed-name  vias can cause problems in hierarchical flows as the
              fixed-names from different  blocks  may  collide.  Parameterized
              via-names  can  be freely changed by applications and avoid this
              problem. If the design has odd-mgrid width wires or  pins,  this
              option is normally a good choice.

              If this parameter is selected as auto, it is true for OpenAccess
              design, false for non-OpenAccess design.

              Default: auto

       -top_enclosure {<overhang1 overhang2>}
              Generates  vias with the specified top enclosure values, without
              modifying the LEF file. Set the -ignore_viarule_enclosure  para-
              meter  to  false  while using this parameter, so that the engine
              can compare the specified  <overhang1>  and  <overhang2>  values
              with the Via Rule Generate values.

              The  <overhang1>  and  <overhang2>  values must be above the Via
              Rule Generate values.

              When the -top_enclosure parameter is used, the via is covered by
              metal layers on two opposite sides by at least <overhang1>  dis-
              tance,  and  on the other two sides by at least <overhang2> dis-
              tance. The via generation code then  chooses  the  direction  of
              overhang  that  best  maximizes the number of cuts to fit in the
              generated via. See the example below:

       -use_track_offset {true | false}
              Uses track offset.

              Default: false

       -use_trim_metal_enclosure {true | false}
              Forces the tool to use enclosures with the trimmed layer.

              Default: false

       -viarule_preference {default | predefined | generated | <list_of_via
       rule/cell_names> | <file_name>}
              Sets the preferred via-rule usage.  Use  this  parameter  before
              running the fcroute, sroute, or power planning commands.

              * default

                Use  the  first DRC clean predefined viarule or auto rule that
                can bring maximum cut area.

              * predefined

                Uses the predefined via rule defined  in  the  LEF  technology
                file as the preferred usage.

              * generated

                Uses the generated via rule defined in the LEF technology file
                as the preferred usage.

              * list of via rule/cell names

                Uses the list of via rules/cells as the preferred usage.

              * file name

                Uses via rules/cells which are contained in the specific file.

              This  parameter  works  in the incremental mode. See the example
              below:

              setViaGenMode -viarule_preference {V1 V2}

              setViaGenMode -viarule_preference {V3}

              getViaGenMode -viarule_preference

              V1 V2 V3

              Default: default

Example
       The following command creates a virtual trim grid  for  PG  hookup  via
       generation:

       setViaGenMode  -hookup_virtual_trim_grid  {-layer  M1 -mask1 {-pitch p1
       -core_offset s1 } -mask2 { -pitch p2 -core_offset s2 }}

